1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,760
 - Hello and welcome to our lecture on SQL.

2
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:06,920
 So this is a very, very short introduction to SQL.

3
00:00:06,920 --> 00:00:11,380
 I love SQL, I was talking to a student the other day

4
00:00:11,380 --> 00:00:13,880
 and they were like, "SQL's my favorite language."

5
00:00:13,880 --> 00:00:15,940
 And I said, "I have to agree that SQL

6
00:00:15,940 --> 00:00:18,600
 "is my favorite language, too."

7
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,240
 Because SQL is so beautiful,

8
00:00:21,240 --> 00:00:23,220
 you don't even need to write loops in SQL.

9
00:00:23,220 --> 00:00:25,160
 We write loops in languages like Python

10
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:27,120
 just because we have to.

11
00:00:27,120 --> 00:00:30,840
 The problem is, is that SQL is just, is perfect,

12
00:00:30,840 --> 00:00:33,240
 but it's not the way we could write something

13
00:00:33,240 --> 00:00:36,120
 as complex as Linux or Python.

14
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:38,740
 And so SQL's not really the way computers think.

15
00:00:38,740 --> 00:00:41,900
 We have these things called database engines.

16
00:00:41,900 --> 00:00:44,580
 And these database engines make things work

17
00:00:44,580 --> 00:00:46,180
 really, really well.

18
00:00:46,180 --> 00:00:49,500
 And so, SQL is a great way to organize data,

19
00:00:49,500 --> 00:00:53,300
 but a lot of work has gone into keeping that data organized

20
00:00:53,300 --> 00:00:54,480
 and making it simple.

21
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:56,920
 So there's a, it's like there's this abstraction

22
00:00:56,920 --> 00:01:00,360
 and it's a lot of work to make that abstraction work.

23
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:02,400
 So I want to start out with a little bit of history,

24
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:04,780
 sort of before databases.

25
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:08,940
 And you might think, "Well, before databases,

26
00:01:08,940 --> 00:01:09,920
 "how could that be?"

27
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:11,620
 Well, you know, it's in the old days

28
00:01:11,620 --> 00:01:15,620
 and if you watch old computer, movies featuring computers,

29
00:01:15,620 --> 00:01:18,920
 you see pictures that have these,

30
00:01:18,920 --> 00:01:20,840
 you see pictures that have these tape machines

31
00:01:20,840 --> 00:01:22,220
 in the background and they're spinning.

32
00:01:22,220 --> 00:01:25,480
 And the spinning of the tape machine is the sort of

33
00:01:25,480 --> 00:01:28,500
 physical manifestation of computation.

34
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:31,200
 And it had to do with the fact that in the old days,

35
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:33,840
 computers did not have enough data

36
00:01:33,840 --> 00:01:37,000
 to store all of their data in the memory or on a disk.

37
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,620
 We didn't even have disks in the early days.

38
00:01:39,620 --> 00:01:41,440
 In the early days, tapes were what we had.

39
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:44,560
 And we used kind of a variation of audio tapes.

40
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:48,840
 And instead of on audio, they contained data, zeros and ones.

41
00:01:48,840 --> 00:01:50,920
 And so the way things would work in the old days

42
00:01:50,920 --> 00:01:53,500
 so that you could have a database, as it were,

43
00:01:53,500 --> 00:01:57,560
 was the database was all of your data recorded onto a tape.

44
00:01:57,560 --> 00:02:01,800
 And the key thing to a tape is that it was a physical thing

45
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:04,500
 and so you had to rewind it and go forwards and backwards.

46
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:07,920
 And most of you probably never even have seen a cassette tape

47
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:09,800
 or a track tape or a reel-to-reel tape.

48
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:14,600
 But it's a physical, long, thousand foot piece of plastic

49
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:16,280
 and to get the data at the end,

50
00:02:16,280 --> 00:02:19,000
 you had to spin it until you got there.

51
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,320
 And so it wasn't what we call random access,

52
00:02:21,320 --> 00:02:23,220
 which means that in a random access,

53
00:02:23,220 --> 00:02:25,480
 whether it's memory or the disk drive,

54
00:02:25,480 --> 00:02:27,920
 random access allows you to get to any place

55
00:02:27,920 --> 00:02:29,760
 roughly in a fixed amount of time.

56
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:32,200
 Whereas if you're close to something on a tape,

57
00:02:32,200 --> 00:02:33,480
 you can get to it very quickly.

58
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:35,760
 If you're far away, you gotta go, "Boo!"

59
00:02:35,760 --> 00:02:38,280
 and then wait and then come back.

60
00:02:38,280 --> 00:02:43,280
 So this led to a pattern where every night,

61
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:47,540
 we would take the tape from yesterday's account balances.

62
00:02:47,540 --> 00:02:49,040
 Let's just say we're a bank

63
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:51,000
 and we're people coming up the window,

64
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,760
 putting in money, taking out money.

65
00:02:52,760 --> 00:02:54,040
 And then what we would do

66
00:02:54,040 --> 00:02:56,120
 is we would put all of the transactions,

67
00:02:56,120 --> 00:02:58,720
 sometimes on physically punched cards,

68
00:02:58,720 --> 00:03:01,080
 and then we would sort them, right?

69
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:03,680
 And let's just say we have 26 accounts

70
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:07,160
 and you know, person C shows up with a little,

71
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:11,000
 you know, adds $10 and person F shows up

72
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,960
 and subtracts $10 and et cetera, et cetera.

73
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:17,280
 And then what we would have at night,

74
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:18,440
 we would get these all sorted

75
00:03:18,440 --> 00:03:19,820
 and there were physical machines

76
00:03:19,820 --> 00:03:22,880
 that would actually sort these in the earliest of days.

77
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:27,880
 And then we would have the old balance A, B, C, D, E, F

78
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:33,120
 sitting on a tape in order, sorted in order.

79
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:36,520
 And we would start a process after the bank closed

80
00:03:36,520 --> 00:03:41,120
 where we would read the first record off the tape, like A.

81
00:03:41,120 --> 00:03:46,120
 We would read the first transaction off the cards

82
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:47,580
 and we would compare them.

83
00:03:47,580 --> 00:03:52,580
 And if the tape was earlier than the transaction or lower,

84
00:03:52,580 --> 00:03:54,920
 we would just copy it.

85
00:03:54,920 --> 00:03:56,080
 So we'd copy it.

86
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:58,920
 And then so the B would compare to the C

87
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:01,720
 and B would get copied and then C would come across.

88
00:04:01,720 --> 00:04:03,960
 And then we'd realize that the C data,

89
00:04:03,960 --> 00:04:06,200
 we would have to update the C data

90
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:08,160
 and add $10 to the balance.

91
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:09,320
 And then we'd write that.

92
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:10,940
 And you'll notice as we're writing this,

93
00:04:10,940 --> 00:04:13,000
 we are sorting, it's in sorted order.

94
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,240
 Then we would copy D, we have nothing for D

95
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:16,720
 and it would just get copied.

96
00:04:16,720 --> 00:04:19,080
 We copy E, we'd have nothing for E

97
00:04:19,080 --> 00:04:20,360
 and it would just get copied.

98
00:04:20,360 --> 00:04:21,760
 And then we would have, oops,

99
00:04:21,760 --> 00:04:23,440
 forgot to put F on this picture.

100
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:26,120
 We would have F and we'd subtract 10 and we would copy it.

101
00:04:26,120 --> 00:04:27,380
 And then we would be done.

102
00:04:27,380 --> 00:04:28,820
 We would be done with the kind of stuff

103
00:04:28,820 --> 00:04:31,040
 that we had to do that night.

104
00:04:31,040 --> 00:04:34,120
 And then what we would do is we'd have this new updated data

105
00:04:34,120 --> 00:04:36,600
 that was all sorted in account order.

106
00:04:36,600 --> 00:04:39,740
 And then the next night we would move the tape,

107
00:04:39,740 --> 00:04:41,600
 the new would be the old tape

108
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:43,760
 and we would do it over and over and over again.

109
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:47,040
 And sometimes these processes would run for four or five

110
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:48,600
 hours 'cause the tapes were long

111
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:50,440
 or it got to be multiple tapes.

112
00:04:50,440 --> 00:04:53,920
 And so a lot of computing was done sort of

113
00:04:53,920 --> 00:04:55,980
 after the banks closed at five o'clock.

114
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:57,560
 Then a group of people would come in.

115
00:04:57,560 --> 00:04:59,800
 We called them operators and they would mount these tapes

116
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:01,760
 and run these jobs and just sit there

117
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:04,440
 and watch these tapes spin as the data was being copied

118
00:05:04,440 --> 00:05:05,840
 from one to the other.

119
00:05:05,840 --> 00:05:09,760
 And so, yeah, that's pretty cool.

120
00:05:09,760 --> 00:05:12,440
 Thankfully, that's not how we do it anymore.

121
00:05:12,440 --> 00:05:14,600
 The thing that made it so we don't have to do this

122
00:05:14,600 --> 00:05:16,540
 is the invention of disk drives.

123
00:05:16,540 --> 00:05:22,520
 And disk drives are magnetic media just like tape drives,

124
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:24,640
 but the difference was is they were

125
00:05:24,640 --> 00:05:26,100
 on these spinning platters.

126
00:05:26,100 --> 00:05:29,600
 And so what you could do is the data was

127
00:05:29,600 --> 00:05:32,520
 in series of concentric circles on these platters

128
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:35,840
 and then you had a head that could move in and out rapidly.

129
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:38,360
 And so the speed at which you could access data

130
00:05:38,360 --> 00:05:40,540
 was a combination with the speed at which the head

131
00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:42,680
 could move to a certain cylinder

132
00:05:42,680 --> 00:05:45,480
 and you had to wait until the data came around.

133
00:05:45,480 --> 00:05:47,920
 And so sometimes you would have a, you know,

134
00:05:47,920 --> 00:05:50,160
 5,400 revolution per minute.

135
00:05:50,160 --> 00:05:54,240
 So that means that 5,400, 5,000 times per minute,

136
00:05:54,240 --> 00:05:58,200
 which is 100 times a second.

137
00:05:58,200 --> 00:05:59,020
 Can I get there?

138
00:05:59,020 --> 00:05:59,920
 Yeah, 100 times a second.

139
00:05:59,920 --> 00:06:02,280
 Yeah, 100 times a second.

140
00:06:02,280 --> 00:06:05,520
 100 times a second, you'd wait a hundredth of a second

141
00:06:05,520 --> 00:06:06,360
 for it.

142
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:08,560
 And so this is way better than waiting

143
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:11,240
 like a minute and a half, two minutes,

144
00:06:11,240 --> 00:06:13,240
 even 10 minutes to spin up a tape.

145
00:06:13,240 --> 00:06:16,480
 And so the problem was is then we're like, okay,

146
00:06:16,480 --> 00:06:18,440
 now that we have this wonderful technology

147
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:21,120
 and we can store all of our nightly data on a disk

148
00:06:21,120 --> 00:06:24,580
 'cause it's enough space, how do we build technology

149
00:06:24,580 --> 00:06:25,960
 to make really good use of this?

150
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:28,960
 And a lot of research, a lot of computer science,

151
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:32,820
 a lot of vendor research went into understanding

152
00:06:32,820 --> 00:06:35,400
 how to best use this new disk thing.

153
00:06:35,400 --> 00:06:37,500
 I remember talking to people like,

154
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:39,240
 'cause we used to use floppy disk works

155
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:43,080
 where they were much slower so they didn't go 5,400.

156
00:06:43,080 --> 00:06:46,560
 So it might take a quarter of a second to move the head

157
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:50,000
 and it might take almost a second to spin it around,

158
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,380
 which was still way faster than 10 minutes, right?

159
00:06:52,380 --> 00:06:54,320
 So it's like about a second to get to anywhere

160
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:56,160
 on a floppy disk.

161
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:59,480
 And we would build approaches to storing data

162
00:06:59,480 --> 00:07:01,900
 and we would start with this physical thing

163
00:07:01,900 --> 00:07:03,500
 and you would hear it grunting and moving

164
00:07:03,500 --> 00:07:04,420
 and grunting and moving.

165
00:07:04,420 --> 00:07:05,760
 And then you would come up with a better way

166
00:07:05,760 --> 00:07:08,360
 to store the data and then it'd grunt and move less

167
00:07:08,360 --> 00:07:09,960
 and your thing would go faster.

168
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:11,460
 So this was like a research thing.

169
00:07:11,460 --> 00:07:13,620
 It was like, it was good old days

170
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:15,480
 when computers actually made noises

171
00:07:15,480 --> 00:07:18,760
 and you could, it could change your code inside computers.

172
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:22,120
 And the first thing of course we did was just took

173
00:07:22,120 --> 00:07:24,380
 those sequential master updates and put them on,

174
00:07:24,380 --> 00:07:26,280
 but that turned out to not be the best.

175
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:27,880
 And that was sort of the researches,

176
00:07:27,880 --> 00:07:30,640
 not just how can we do what we used to do on data

177
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:33,440
 that couldn't be random accessed, randomly accessed,

178
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:36,320
 and instead say let's take advantage of it.

179
00:07:36,320 --> 00:07:39,040
 And so a lot of research, a lot of vendors,

180
00:07:39,040 --> 00:07:41,680
 there was a lot of very expensive software

181
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:44,340
 that people bought to say, look, you know,

182
00:07:44,340 --> 00:07:47,120
 you're a bank and you really and truly wanna,

183
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:49,360
 you know, know how this works.

184
00:07:49,360 --> 00:07:53,040
 And so what happened was is in the 60s and 70s,

185
00:07:53,040 --> 00:07:55,840
 the computer vendors were fighting

186
00:07:55,840 --> 00:07:58,120
 and they would come up with a technique

187
00:07:58,120 --> 00:08:01,000
 which, you know, compared to our current database technique

188
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:02,920
 was just trivially simple.

189
00:08:02,920 --> 00:08:04,720
 But it took a lot of work back then.

190
00:08:04,720 --> 00:08:08,680
 And they would fight with all the other computer vendors

191
00:08:08,680 --> 00:08:12,360
 and they would say our index sequential mechanism is better

192
00:08:12,360 --> 00:08:16,040
 and vendor two would say our network approach is better.

193
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:17,800
 And then they would sit and they would sort of struggle

194
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:20,560
 with each other and then the poor customers would be like,

195
00:08:20,560 --> 00:08:22,160
 I don't even know what you're talking about.

196
00:08:22,160 --> 00:08:25,360
 And so then they would just buy the stuff from the vendor

197
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:28,760
 who took them out to golf or the best lunch

198
00:08:28,760 --> 00:08:30,600
 or took them on a trip to Florida.

199
00:08:30,600 --> 00:08:32,760
 And then they would just, you know, adapt to whatever that

200
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:33,600
 vendor did.

201
00:08:33,600 --> 00:08:39,640
 And so it was really kind of scary because we were moving

202
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:42,600
 into a place where you were locked into a vendor.

203
00:08:42,600 --> 00:08:45,040
 And then once you're locked into a vendor,

204
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:45,880
 you're in bad shape.

205
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:49,640
 And so the US government in particular had a ton of money

206
00:08:49,640 --> 00:08:51,760
 and were buying tons of computers, both, you know,

207
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:56,760
 for normal data processing and for strategic things like,

208
00:08:58,040 --> 00:09:00,560
 you know, military stuff.

209
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:02,720
 And so they were buying tons of computers and they knew

210
00:09:02,720 --> 00:09:05,200
 that these vendors, if they got to the point

211
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:07,660
 where they locked them into a single vendor,

212
00:09:07,660 --> 00:09:10,840
 that the vendor would just be able to dictate the price.

213
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:14,520
 And so the federal government through NIST,

214
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:17,440
 the National Institute of Standards and Technology,

215
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:20,280
 decided that databases needed a standard.

216
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:23,860
 They needed a way so that we could talk to any database

217
00:09:23,860 --> 00:09:26,160
 from any vendor using the same technique

218
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:31,600
 and not have to, you know, do one vendor.

219
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:32,660
 And then if you switched vendors,

220
00:09:32,660 --> 00:09:34,400
 you had to completely rewrite your software.

221
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:38,800
 And so they didn't, the NIST didn't specify how this

222
00:09:38,800 --> 00:09:41,520
 abstraction, the standard was going to work.

223
00:09:41,520 --> 00:09:43,160
 They just brought the vendors in and said,

224
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:46,760
 we're gonna stop using your software if you don't come up

225
00:09:46,760 --> 00:09:48,200
 with a standard.

226
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:51,220
 And it was a perfect time because even though the vendors

227
00:09:51,220 --> 00:09:54,300
 thought they had everything was perfect and wonderful,

228
00:09:55,680 --> 00:09:57,920
 there was a lot of upside.

229
00:09:57,920 --> 00:10:00,240
 And in particular, there was this concept of relational

230
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:04,120
 databases, which back then was more of a mathematical theory

231
00:10:04,120 --> 00:10:06,560
 of a better way to store and retrieve data than it was

232
00:10:06,560 --> 00:10:09,280
 a practically implemented available technology.

233
00:10:09,280 --> 00:10:13,460
 And so SQL, and this is Liz Fong, who I went and I did

234
00:10:13,460 --> 00:10:14,300
 an interview at NIST.

235
00:10:14,300 --> 00:10:17,340
 She talks about the early days, it's a great interview.

236
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:21,480
 The early days of how this SQL standard really made so much

237
00:10:21,480 --> 00:10:24,280
 sense and really fixed the industry and got the industry

238
00:10:24,280 --> 00:10:27,580
 working really nicely and I recommend that you take a look

239
00:10:27,580 --> 00:10:31,200
 at this video, just so you can kind of see.

240
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:36,000
 Now, what SQL basically said was, is that let's not worry

241
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,600
 so much about where that data is actually on disk.

242
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:43,680
 Because the earlier database approaches were, we programmers

243
00:10:43,680 --> 00:10:46,860
 would know that there was cylinders and positions and we

244
00:10:46,860 --> 00:10:50,240
 would place things in certain ways and we would make indexes

245
00:10:50,240 --> 00:10:52,320
 and we would look at the indexes ourselves.

246
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:55,600
 So all kind of different things, we would read to one place

247
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:57,960
 on the disk and that would have an address of the next place

248
00:10:57,960 --> 00:10:59,720
 we're supposed to read on the disk.

249
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:04,480
 And they said, you know what, let's not worry so much

250
00:11:04,480 --> 00:11:07,480
 about the physical storage structure on the disk.

251
00:11:07,480 --> 00:11:12,240
 But instead, let's come up with a language by which we can

252
00:11:12,240 --> 00:11:17,240
 express what we want to read, write, update, and delete

253
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:19,840
 on the disk in a really simple language.

254
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:23,120
 And then we can build a piece of software that there could be

255
00:11:23,120 --> 00:11:26,840
 many disk formats underneath that and then we could all

256
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:30,160
 sort of just use this language and you could buy vendor A

257
00:11:30,160 --> 00:11:32,400
 and use this language and vendor B and use this language

258
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:35,280
 and then you could even benchmark it and say, here's a bunch

259
00:11:35,280 --> 00:11:38,400
 of stuff in this language, which vendor can run this faster?

260
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:43,400
 And so the NIST also had a series of benchmarks, TPC,

261
00:11:43,400 --> 00:11:44,800
 or some of the benchmarks.

262
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:50,560
 And so what they did is they basically made it so that this

263
00:11:50,560 --> 00:11:52,720
 was like a beautiful and simple language.

264
00:11:52,720 --> 00:11:55,800
 And it's what we call SQL, I think at some point

265
00:11:55,800 --> 00:11:58,640
 it was called the Simple Query Language.

266
00:11:58,640 --> 00:12:01,840
 And it is the language that we use to talk to databases.

267
00:12:01,840 --> 00:12:05,760
 And the interesting thing is what SQL allowed us to do,

268
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:08,800
 really in the '60s and '70s when it first came out,

269
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:11,920
 was to talk to the old style databases,

270
00:12:11,920 --> 00:12:15,160
 like index sequential and network style databases.

271
00:12:15,160 --> 00:12:18,280
 And as this new form called relational databases,

272
00:12:18,280 --> 00:12:20,960
 which had like this awesome mathematical underpinning,

273
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:23,160
 but was implemented badly in the first time,

274
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:26,200
 we could just say, oh, we're kind of, this is all,

275
00:12:26,200 --> 00:12:28,640
 when the performance of relational databases

276
00:12:28,640 --> 00:12:30,560
 got to the point where it was as good

277
00:12:30,560 --> 00:12:34,840
 as the other databases, then we could just switch

278
00:12:34,840 --> 00:12:36,800
 and we could talk the same SQL.

279
00:12:36,800 --> 00:12:40,520
 So it allowed an amazing innovation over a 10

280
00:12:40,520 --> 00:12:44,040
 or even 15 year period where the abstraction

281
00:12:44,040 --> 00:12:48,400
 allowed us to improve databases in a wonderful way

282
00:12:48,400 --> 00:12:50,800
 without really having to change how we as programmers

283
00:12:50,800 --> 00:12:51,960
 used them.

284
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:54,400
 Pretty dang awesome, I'll be honest.

285
00:12:54,400 --> 00:12:57,400
 And so I've been talking about this idea

286
00:12:57,400 --> 00:12:59,680
 of relational databases and relational databases,

287
00:12:59,680 --> 00:13:02,280
 and I'll admit that when I first saw relational databases

288
00:13:02,280 --> 00:13:05,320
 in the early 1980s, I'm like, this is crap.

289
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:08,080
 Because again, I could hear floppy disks

290
00:13:08,080 --> 00:13:09,560
 and I knew that we were moving the thing

291
00:13:09,560 --> 00:13:11,600
 and I had so much awareness of what was going on

292
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:13,640
 and I loved that awareness.

293
00:13:13,640 --> 00:13:16,680
 And the relational databases sort of like hid that,

294
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:19,920
 hid what was going on behind this layer

295
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:22,280
 and it turned out that whenever I used it,

296
00:13:22,280 --> 00:13:25,240
 it was slower 'cause it wasn't yet clever.

297
00:13:25,240 --> 00:13:27,200
 And so relational databases started out

298
00:13:27,200 --> 00:13:29,720
 as a mathematical idea as the theoretical best way

299
00:13:29,720 --> 00:13:33,320
 to represent networks of data with columns and rows

300
00:13:33,320 --> 00:13:35,360
 and connections and joins and we'll talk about

301
00:13:35,360 --> 00:13:36,560
 all that eventually.

302
00:13:36,560 --> 00:13:42,120
 And it was a beautiful idea and the mathematics was right.

303
00:13:42,120 --> 00:13:45,520
 It just took a long time to get to the point

304
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:48,760
 where it turned, the superior mathematics

305
00:13:48,760 --> 00:13:53,760
 of relational databases worked out better

306
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:55,920
 than the highly cleverly optimized

307
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:58,280
 previous generation database systems.

308
00:13:58,280 --> 00:14:01,480
 So there's a lot of common database systems

309
00:14:01,480 --> 00:14:03,520
 that you'll run across.

310
00:14:03,520 --> 00:14:06,760
 Some of them are open source, some of them are commercial.

311
00:14:06,760 --> 00:14:10,400
 PostgreSQL and MySQL are open source.

312
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:12,320
 PostgreSQL is probably the more intricate

313
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:13,400
 and complex and rich.

314
00:14:13,400 --> 00:14:16,640
 Oracle is a intricate, complex and rich database

315
00:14:16,640 --> 00:14:18,800
 that's available for lots and lots of money.

316
00:14:18,800 --> 00:14:22,440
 And Microsoft has a database called SQL Server.

317
00:14:22,440 --> 00:14:25,640
 And all these databases that we're seeing evolved

318
00:14:25,640 --> 00:14:29,240
 in a sense after the SQL spec existed.

319
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:30,960
 So they just kind of built SQL.

